that must be considered if experimental results are used to understand the temporal and spatial scales of actual ecosystems.The complexity of ecosystems complicates experimental design. How, for example, does a scientist draw boundaries when studying species effects and interactions? Once these boundaries are drawn, how does one treat factors external to that study? Will the failure to consider external factors affect one's ability to extrapolate information across temporal and spatial scales? This volume provides a compilation from a broad range of ecologists with extensive experimental research experience that addresses these and other questions of scaling relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEcologyvMethodology. 0aEcologyxMethodology. 0aEcologíavMetodología. 0aNATUREvEcology. 0aNATUREvEcosystems &ampxHabitatsvWilderness. 0aSCIENCEvEnvironmental Science (see also ChemistryvEnvironmental). 0aSCIENCEvLife SciencesvEcology. 7aNATURE / Ecosystems & Habitats / General.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Timothy F. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlumenshine, Steve C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoynton, Walter R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreitburg, Denise L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrost, Thomas M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, Robert H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHagy, James D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatfield, Colleen A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeath, Michael R., econtributor.4ctb4